    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-09-03T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-09-03T01:00:00-05:00" n="629"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d629">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/5525: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1"
                            type="from">Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-09-03T14:00:00+08:00"
                            >September 3, 1932—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received September 3—5:38 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1059. My 1043, August 31, 8 a.m. [<hi rend="italic">p.m.?</hi>]<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d629fn4">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_214">p. 214</ref>.</note>
                    American Naval Attaché in recent conversation with <persName
                        corresp="frus1932v03#p_WCH1">Colonel Watari</persName> (former Japanese
                    Military Attaché to Washington) who has been attached to Japanese <pb
                        facs="0673" n="575" xml:id="pg_575"/> assessor with League Commission was
                    told by the latter that the Japanese, except in the event of serious
                    provocation, has [<hi rend="italic">have</hi>] no intention of occupying the
                    Peiping-Tientsin area. He stated that he personally disapproved of the night
                    maneuvers of the Japanese Legation guard into Chinese territory and that he has
                    so informed the local guard commander. <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_WCH1"
                        >Colonel Watari</persName> stated that he was going to Tokyo in a few days
                    to take up his duties as a member of the General Staff and that he felt sure
                    that he could bring the necessary pressure to bear to stop the maneuvers. He
                    also stated that of all places Peiping was the one where fighting should be
                    avoided.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
